Difference Between All Three

| Feature             | ReplicationController | ReplicaSet  | Deployment      |
| ------------------- | --------------------- | ----------- | --------------- |
| Maintains pod count | Yes                   | Yes         | Yes             |
| Equality selector   | Yes                   | Yes         | Yes             |
| Set-based selector  | No                    | Yes         | Yes             |
| Rolling update      | No (manual)           | No (manual) | Yes (automatic) |
| Rollback            | No                    | No          | Yes             |
| Pause/Resume update | No                    | No          | Yes             |
| Still recommended   | No                    | Rarely      | Yes             |

Deployment

what is Rolling update and rollback

A rolling update means updating pods gradually one by one instead of all at once.

With Rolling Update:
Old pods die ONE BY ONE → New pods start ONE BY ONE
         ↓
   ZERO DOWNTIME ✅

# Or edit directly
kubectl edit deployment frontend

# Or apply updated yaml
kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml

Rollback
Rollback means going back to a previous version if something goes wrong.

v1 running fine ✅
   ↓
Update to v2 → something broken ❌
   ↓
Rollback to v1 → back to normal ✅

How Rollback Works Internally

Deployment keeps history of ReplicaSets:

ReplicaSet v1  (nginx:1.21)  ← scaled down but NOT deleted
ReplicaSet v2  (nginx:1.22)  ← current, broken ❌

Rollback → ReplicaSet v1 scales back up ✅

Rollback Commands

# Rollback to previous version immediately
kubectl rollout undo deployment/frontend

# See rollout history
kubectl rollout history deployment/frontend

# Rollback to specific version
kubectl rollout undo deployment/frontend --to-revision=2

